Answer: Step 1: Prepare the cyclohexyl ketone branch by O-alkylating 4-(hydroxymethyl)cyclohexanone with 2-bromo-1,1-difluoroethane (base) to give 4-((2,2-difluoroethoxy)methyl)cyclohexanone | Step 2: Reductive amination of enantiopure trans-2-aminocyclohexan-1-ol (the enantiomer matching the target) with N-Boc-4-piperidone using NaBH(OAc)3 to give trans-2-[(1-Boc-piperidin-4-yl)amino]cyclohexan-1-ol | Step 3: Remove Boc (TFA or HCl/dioxane) to obtain trans-2-(piperidin-4-ylamino)cyclohexan-1-ol | Step 4: Reductive amination of that piperidine NH with 4-((2,2-difluoroethoxy)methyl)cyclohexanone (NaBH(OAc)3) to form the tertiary amino alcohol bearing the N-(4-(2,2-difluoroethoxymethyl)cyclohexyl) substituent | Step 5: Cyclocarbonylate the amino alcohol with CDI or triphosgene/base to close the 2-oxazolidinone ring, furnishing O=C1CO[C@H]2CCCC[C@@H]2N1C1CCN(C2CCC(COCC(F)F)CC2)CC1

